article.description: Katie Douglas leads the Sun past the Monarchs Friday night.
article.headline: Sun have too many weapons, burn Monarchs again
article.linkText: Sun have too many weapons, burn Monarchs again
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Here's a pop quiz for Connecticut Sun
opponents.

Who is the Sun's go-to player?

The way the Eastern Conference leaders are playing lately it
could be anybody. And it has been since the franchise's career
leading scorer, Nykesha Sales, was sidelined with an injury.

The defending champion Sacramento Monarchs couldn't solve the
Sun on Friday night and Connecticut took advantage with a 75-68 win
in a rematch of last season's WNBA finals.

Katie Douglas scored 19 points and Lindsay Whalen added 17 in
the victory that extended the Sun's winning streak to a season-high
six games. Taj McWilliams-Franklin dominated inside for Connecticut
(20-6) with 15 points and 14 rebounds, grabbing 10 boards on the
defensive glass.

"It's the same story. You come out and do well. That's how our
system works," McWilliams-Franklin said. "Any one of us could hit
a million shots."

The Sun had four players averaging double figures heading into
the game with a fifth, Whalen, adding just under 10 points. She
made three 3-pointers Friday to match her season total, none bigger
than her final one with just over a minute to play.

McWilliams-Franklin set a franchise record with her ninth
double-double of the season and Douglas, the All-Star game MVP,
also set a team mark by scoring in double figures in 16 straight
games.

Sacramento's 69-63 home win over Connecticut on July 15 was the
Sun's second game without Sales, who was averaging 13.7 points.
She's missed the last eight with a sore Achilles tendon, but the
Sun have hardly flinched, going 7-1 in that stretch.

"We wanted to keep the winning streak going,"
McWilliams-Franklin said. "We didn't want it to end. Not now."

The Monarchs (16-11) have had a tougher time of late, dropping
three straight, all on the road to the top three Eastern Conference
teams -- Connecticut, Indiana and Detroit. Their loss to the Shock
on Wednesday was a 20-point rout.

"We hoped to get one of these three and we didn't get any of
them," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "All three of these
teams don't lose many on their home court."

Nicole Powell led Sacramento with 17 points. She had 10 in the
fourth quarter as the Monarchs whittled away at Connecticut's
17-point lead. She hit two straight 3s in the final period and her
jumper with 2:55 left cut the deficit to 67-63. The Monarchs would
get no closer.

The Sun quickly regained some breathing room by going inside to
McWilliams-Franklin for a bucket. The Sun's Asjha Jones followed
with an outside jumper. Whalen helped ice the win with her third
3-pointer of the night with 1:04 left for a 74-65 lead.

McWilliams-Franklin then came up with a key defensive board with
18.5 seconds left, was fouled and made the second of two free
throws to cap the scoring.

"Our defense after the first eight minutes or so of the game
was terrific," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "I know they scored
21 points in the fourth quarter, but Powell had about half of them
with a hand in her face."

The Monarchs got a spark off the bench from Hamchetou Maiga-Ba
with 15 points and DeMya Walker with 10. Walker, who has been
working herself back into game shape after the birth of her
daughter in April, scored eight points in the second quarter as the
Monarchs briefly grabbed the lead at 32-28.

But the Sun responded with a 10-0 run, fueled by back-to-back
buckets from Whalen and closed out the half with a 44-36 lead.

"I think we got frustrated in the first half. That allowed the
deficit to get deeper than it had to be," Walker said. "In the
fourth quarter we showed our grit and our character by fighting
back from 17. You might just roll over and die, but we didn't do
that."

The teams split their season series at 1-1 and wouldn't meet
again unless it was in the finals.

"We've got seven games left and we've just got to tend to our
own business and wish [Connecticut] good luck," Whisenant said.
"We're glad that we're through with them but I would like to see
them one more time."
